subsection.p:
A normal practice is to round off the uncertain amount to one or two non-zero digit and use that absolute uncertainty figure as a guide to round off the main number to the same precision level. In this book, we will round the uncertain part to one nonzero digit by using appropriate powers of 10, if necessary. So, if you somehow ended up with main amount 2.57\text{ cm} with uncertain amount 0.1\text{ cm}, you would use the precision of the uncertain amount and round off the main value to the same precision. Thus, this will become 2.6\text{ cm} with uncertain amount 0.1\text{ cm}
2.57\, \text{cm} \pm 0.1\, \text{cm} \rightarrow 2.6\, \text{cm} \pm 0.1\, \text{cm}.
The pratice of rounding off to reflect the precision present in the uncertain amount is also called keeping the values to significant figures. You do not need to memorize any rules about significant figures; just look at the uncerain part and keep the main value upto that significance. If uncertain part is not given, then we assume that the last digit in the given value must correspond to the uncertain part with uncertainty be one or two units in that digit. Hence, a value 1.576 would just mean 1.576\pm0.001.

solution.p:
To apply rules of significant figures in a calculation, we need to identify the least precise number in the input numbers. Here the length of 1.5\ \text{cm} has two significant figures, the width of  0.600\ \text{cm} and height of 0.105\ \text{cm} each have three.  Thus, the least precise number has two significant digits.  Therefore, the volume will have no more than two significant digits.

	 \text{Volume} \amp =  1.5\ \text{cm} \times 0.600\ \text{cm}\times 0.105\ \text{cm} 
	 \amp = 0.0945\ \text{cm}^3\ \text{(from calculator; incorrect number of digits)}

Now we need to round off the number obtained above to the correct number of significant digits, which is two here.  The final number 0.0945 has one digit to the left of the decimal and four digits to the right of the decimal. The decimal is readily moved to get rid of the leading zeros if we write the number using a power of ten as a multiplier.  Therefore, the only digits which matter are the contiguous non-zero digits, i.e., 9, 4 and 5 here.
